Two Steps of Encapsulation
Step 1

Make variables

private

Example

private String name;

private int age;
Step 2

Provide Getter and Setter methods.

Getter

public String getName() {

    return name;

}

Setter

public void setName(String name) {

    this.name = name;

}
Complete Example
class Student {

    private String name;
    private int age;

    public void setName(String name) {

        this.name = name;

    }

    public void setAge(int age) {

        this.age = age;

    }

    public String getName() {

        return name;

    }

    public int getAge() {

        return age;

    }

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Student s = new Student();

        s.setName("Yash");
        s.setAge(22);

        System.out.println(s.getName());
        System.out.println(s.getAge());

    }

}

Output

Yash
22
Why Not Make Variables Public?
public int age;

Anyone can do

age = -100;

Wrong.

With encapsulation

public void setAge(int age){

    if(age > 0){

        this.age = age;

    }

}

Now

setAge(-100);

Age will not change.

Advantages of Encapsulation
1. Data Security

Hide important data.

2. Data Validation

Check values before storing them.

Example

if(age > 0)
3. Easy Maintenance

Change internal implementation without affecting other classes.

4. Better Control

Decide who can read or modify data.

5. Flexibility

You can later change how data is stored without changing the code that uses the class.

Getter vs Setter
Getter

Used to read data.

getName();

Returns value.

Setter

Used to update data.

setName("Yash");

Changes value.

